<TITLE> Sri Lanka ex-general Fonseka goes on trial </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 COLOMBO, Mar 16 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Former Sri Lankan army chief Sarath Fonseka was set to face a military court on Tuesday on charges of engaging in politics while in office in a trial likely to raise political tensions in the island. Fonseka, who lost a presidential election to incumbent Mahinda Rajapaksa earlier this year, was arrested last month following allegations that he was plotting a coup against the government. He is also accused of violating procedures for military supplies. The former army commander has denied the allegations and said these were political motivated and aimed at denying him the chance to run in parliamentary elections next month. Protests after the arrest of Fonseka dragged down the island nation's share market but stocks have since recovered, event though foreign investors have been net sellers. On Monday, the share index hit a fresh all-time high before closing flat due to profit-taking. Street protests, strikes and labour unrest could have a ripple impact on Sri Lanka's $40 billion economy, which is forecast to grow more than 6 percent this year. Fonseka's allies questioned the logic of trying him in a military court when he no longer was in uniform. "The arrest and detention are illegal as General Fonseka does not fall under military law," said Somawansa Amarasinghe, the leader of Marxists Janatha Vimukthi Peremuna (JVP) party. A military spokesman declined any comment on the court martial. Fonseka and Rajapaksa worked together to end a 25-year war against Tamil Tiger separatists last year but soon fell out. Fonseka lost by an 18 percentage point margin to Rajapaksa in the January poll, after which he accused the president of rigging the vo
